@node "gr1" "Croins Vs WBsteriods"

@{fg shine} Croins Vs WBsteriods@{fg text}

 Croins and WBsteriods are two totally different games, although they are
based around the classic Asteriods, each of them has there own little extra
features.

 WBsteriods is the classic graphics in a Workbench window version, the 
graphics are very basic, and the colour are limited according to your 
Workbench set up (or by default, 4 colours!) As I said in issue 10 it slows
down on the later levels because there are loads of asteriods on the screen
at once, this really makes the gameplay a load of rubbish, but if you have 
an expanded computer, Fast RAM extra (unlike me) it should be fine, (Is 
this try Ed?). The best part in WBsteriods is when you fire, instead of a 
naff ball firing (Like in Croins) you get a line comming out, and as it 
moves you get a kind of shadow effect with the white line changing colour 
to red and gradually getting fainter.

 Croins, in my opinion is the better version, it is an adapted version of 
the classic asteriods and with the authors own graphics, music and several 
options, it is the choise for the average games player, unless you are a 
mega classics fan (like the Ed?!!?!)[-ed I hate clasics, stop saying this!]. 
The really nice thing about Croins is that you can disable the annoying 
Hyper-Space option, this is really handy as when I move I think pressing 
DOWN will slow me down but I end up in hyper-space and somewhere else on 
the screen! The graphics are great, there nothing like those seen in 
WBsteriods!

 Unless you are looking for the classic Asteriods, in which case you 
should buy a Commodore 64, get Croins, the graphics are better, the 
gameplay fernominable, and great lastability!

@{b}Overall Winner@{ub} : Croins

@{b}Reviewed by@{ub}    : Lee Hesselden

