@node "fe1" "The way for Amiga to survive"

@{fg shine} The way for Amiga to survive@{fg text}

 I have been thinking over this for sometime now and it is important that 
the Amiga is handled properly if it will succeed, it is not always down to 
the actual computer to whether it will be popular, there are a number of 
factors that will make a computer successful. Firstly Amiga Int/Inc are 
going to have to cut there losses and charge a low price for the computer, 
they will have to lose profit at first to gain profit in the long run. This 
happend with the Sony Playstation where they charged a lower price than was 
really exceptable for them to charge but there marketing plans worked and 
they ended up being in profit. The less you charge for a computer the more 
the public are likely to want to buy it. Lets be honest who in the right mind 
is going to dump there £1000 Pc when a new Amiga comes out if it is also 
going to be £1000? The new Amigas really need to be aimed at the £500-£700 
price range for the 'normal' every day buyers, with higher spec systems for
graphic designers and more professional uses. 
 The second factor is before the computer is actually lunched Amiga Inc/Int
will have to contact existing big software houses, shops and other 
bussinesses to let the know about the benifits of using the new Amigas.
Software houses will have to be supplied with free top of the range Amigas so 
that they can start work on new projects or convert there existing products 
to the Amiga platform. This will allow the Amiga to be lunched with an 
already existing product range, no one will buy the Amiga if there is no 
software for it, even if there is promissed software in the future people 
will see a computer and no software, then look at the PC and see a huge range 
of software and of course choose the PC.
 The next factor is advertising, back when the Amiga was lunched there was 
absolutly no advertising but the Amiga still sold well, times have changed 
and for customers to buy things they want to see what it can do and they want 
to know about it. TV advertisments will be needed to show off what the Amiga 
is capable of otherwise everyone will be thinking 'I remember Amiga 500s, 
they where rubbish' so they won't buy an Amiga.
 And lastly it will need to be to some point a plug in and play type
of computer for new computer users that no nothing about them. It needs to 
come with built in internet software and other neccesary things to make it 
easier for the begginer to use.

Article by : Chris Seward

