@endnode

@node "fe2" "Work in progress"

@{fg shine} Domiantion - Work in progress@{fg text}

                           ___
                           / /__ __ ·__ __ __ ·__ __
                          /_//_////// //-/ / //_// /
                             @{b}@{fg shine}@{bg fill}The Diary of a Game@{fg text}@{bg back}@{ub}

                          By Jamie Solomons of Amiga1

                                  @{b}Part  One@{ub}


 @{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

 Welcome to the first part of the diary. I am Jamie, the major programmer of
 Domination. This diary follows the progress of the game from the very
 beginning to where it is now and gives some handy hints about making your
 own game.

 The diary details the revamp of the game. A lot of the game has already
 been coded but it was not looking as good as we had hoped so we dumped the
 code, redrew the graphics and started from stratch. Our first design had 96
 ships, this was very nice and all it took ages to design each one and we
 had to take RAM into consideration. The new design has only 16 ships but
 that's all you need. You have a nice selection of items to equip each ship
 with, such as transporters and cloaking devices which were not present in
 the original game design. You couldn't choose the weapons to put on your
 ship because they were set but and they are interchangable via a beautiful
 drag and drop system that I have just finished. In the revamp we hope to
 allow control of ships within a star system as well as between systems.
 This is only an idea and we still need to sit down and discuss whether or
 not it is actually practical (programming-wise).

 Throughout this diary I will show you the changes we made and for what
 reasons. Once I have reached the stage that we got to in the development of
 the original game I'll keep you up to date with the developments as and
 when they happen. I keep a weekly diary for the game so I don't forget
 anything. (I might even reveal some secrets of the game such as cheat
 modes, hidden races, secret weapons, ect. :)

 N.B. AMOS commands will be shown in @{i}italics@{ui}.


 @{b}@{u}How it all Began@{ub}@{uu}

 Mark suggested the idea of making a space command game a bit like the PD
 game Conquest. I didn't really like the idea because I don't like Conquest
 but, unknown to Mark his suggestion had lit the flame to a big project -
 Domination. I began thinking about what I wanted in the game.
 
 I wanted to give the game a two-player option for null-modem link-up.
 I also wanted to give the game depth by having no single set objective.
 Players have a communications window in which they can type transmissions
 freely. You could wage war, set peace treaties or whatever you could think
 up. You could gang up against an enemy race or attack a space station.
 There are no limits!

 I wanted there to be other races as well as the ability to expand your
 civilisation by terraforming and colonising other planets in other systems.
 You could even terraform Pluto and setup a base there! I hoped to have a
 lot of secrets in the game as these are fun to discover. Ultimately I
 wanted a game with less "hack and slay" and more fun.

 To tackle the game I went along with Mark's idea to get the initial
 structure of the game off the ground and then, bit-by-bit add in the
 colour.


 @{b}@{u}The Programming Language@{ub}@{uu}

 The first thing that we did was figure out which programming langage to
 use. The only two that we had a hope of using were AMOS Pro and Blitz
 Basic 2. We weren't really experienced enough with the internal workings
 of the Amiga to use Blitz (I did try, but I found it difficult to display
 the screens I wanted; or slices, as they're called in Blitz). But there was
 a problem with AMOS Pro. Being an interpreted language we needed a
 compiler. I have the AMOS 1.3 compiler but that meant avoiding AMOS Pro
 commands and not having more than 16 banks. We decided to still use AMOS
 Pro commands and find someone to compile the game for us (Mr Seward has
 offered so you'll probably be hearing a lot more from the Domination team
 from now on!)

 AMOS Pro is not the best language for serious development but it suits our
 needs. It's a very flexable language and easy to use. Considering the
 amount of coding involved in Domination, we thought it was the best choice.
 I have always wanted to make a game but never took it seriously (probably
 because of the amount of work involved).


 @{b}@{u}Week One@{ub}@{uu}

 The first thing that we did for the game was redesign the main screen and
 its interface. This originally consisted of three screens (screens in AMOS
 do not have to fill the entire display, so you can have more than one
 visible at a time). Here's the first design of the main screen...

                    +--------------------------------+
                    |        Map control bar         |
                    +--------------------------------+
                    |                                |
                    |                                |
                    |                                |
                    |           Map Screen           |
                    |                                |
                    |                                |
                    |                                |
                    +--------------------------------+
                    |  The base bar (as we call it), |
                    |  it controls the game.         |
                    +--------------------------------+

 This was a good design but we found that the map control bar reduced the
 map screen by too much and so it had to go. We are now using a tab system
 for the game, allowing us to get a lot of information onto the base bar.
 This system shows a lot of information and doesn't look too cluttered.

 During the construction of the original game we had a good idea of what we
 wanted but I have to admit that we didn't plan it very well. To begin with
 we just let the game develop on its own and hoped that everything fell into
 place. This is bad programming tecnique and we shouldn't have done it. We
 have changed this by the careful planning of this revamp.

 The base bar had space for a message bar, a graphical display of the
 selected system, brief information on the system, buttons to access menus,
 a panel for communications and space for a few other buttons. The first
 design for this bar didn't look too good (improvments have been made).

 @{"   Basebar   " system "Screenshots/showiff Screenshots/dom1.iff"} - Click here to see the design for the original base bar.
 @{" New Basebar " system "Screenshots/showiff Screenshots/dom2.iff"} - Click here to see the new design for the base bar.

 We dropped the idea of a permanent graphical display of the current system
 and put it on a tab because it's not actually used that much in the game.
 The gadget with the word lock next to it is actually a tick box (more about
 this another time). We also went for a more graphical approach as our first
 design looked a bit boring.
 
 Once we had designed the foundations for the game we started designing the
 menus that could be opened from the base bar. We had buttons for a data
 menu, a colonise/military menu, a trades menu, a government menu, a
 research menu, a mining menu, a help menu and a fleet menu.

 We took the time to discuss the graphics that were to be used on the main
 map screen. As we are not very good at designing graphics, we went for a
 more tactical approach. We decided that the player would be looking down
 upon the galaxy (or part of it) and make military decisions. This might
 sound a bit boring but if you like K-240, Sim City, Dune or any game along
 the same lines then you will love the ideas that we have for Domination.

 @{b}@{u}Week Two@{ub}@{uu}

 We worked out how we were going to display the map. We originally decided
 on a large screen that scrolled around when you moved the pointer to the
 edge of the display. The area that you could see was just a small area of
 the overall map.

                    +----------------------------------+
                    |                                  |
                    |                Map               |
                    |                                  |
                    |                                  |
                    |         +-----------------+      |
                    |         |                 |      |
                    |         |   Viewpoint     |      |
                    |         |(physical screen)|      |
                    |         |                 |      |
                    |         +-----------------+      |
                    |                                  |
                    +----------------------------------+

 This is fine and can allow smooth scrolling (@{i}screen offset@{ui}). The
 problems with it are that you only have a limited screen size (about 1024
 by 1024) and this limits the size of the map. A large 32 colour screen also
 takes up quite a lot of RAM. A solution would be to update the display in
 the region of the screen that is just about to scroll into view. We could
 then make the screen "wrap" and therefore have a huge map. This is a rather
 complicated solution and we prefer the simplicity of a single screen and
 the idea is still open to debate. An idea that I had was to introduce
 wormholes that link to other galaxies (or a different part of the galaxy
 you are in). You could then change the map completely when you click on the
 wormhole, for example.

 We booted up Frontier (Elite 2) to get ideas for some system names. There's
 nothing wrong with taking the names of the systems that are a long distance
 away from from Sol because there are so many of them (I think they are
 generated).

 We considered the kind of symbols that the map was going to display and
 decided that a way was needed of controlling what the map showed. Mark
 at first came up with the idea of a map bar that sits at the top of the
 display with buttons that control what is being shown by the map. We have
 kept the same idea but placed it onto one of the tabs to save space and
 increase the map area that you could see.

 I considered the problem of storing all the information that we needed for
 the game and worried about RAM limitations. These worries were not for my
 Amiga but for those people that @{i}still@{ui} havn't upgraded.

 This is the the Amiga that Domination is being created on:

 Amiga 1200 - 400MB internal IDE Hard Drive, 260MB external IDE Hard Drive,
              170MB external IDE Hard Drive, Mini Tower for HD's, Blizzard
              68030-50MHz accelerator with 16MB SIMM, a 4-Way buffered
              interface, an external floppy drive, Philips monitor, stereo
              output, a mouse, and an 8-bit sound sampler.

 but it's better than Mark's...

 Amiga 500+ - 130MB external Hard Drive, mouse!

 and Chris'...

 PC.. (NOOOOOOOO!)     He sold his Amiga and regrets it ("space" - he says).

 It's not a bad system and it does the job quite nicely.

 This is as far as we have got so look out for part two next month -
 weeks 3 to 5. If you want to contact us about anything, email as at:

                      @{b}chris@amiga1.demon.co.uk@{ub}

    @{" Main Menu " link "Main" } @{" Articles Menu " link "arti" }
@endnode

